Background

In the data folder, you will find data about shark incidents in California between 1950-2022. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

Load the libraries

library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")
library("naniar")

Load the data

Run the following code chunk to import the data.

sharks <- read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv") %>% clean_names()

  1. (1 point) Notice that there are some incidents identified as “NOT COUNTED”. These should be removed from the data because they were either not sharks, unverified, or were provoked. It’s OK to replace the sharks object.
sharks <- sharks %>% 
  filter(incident_num!="NOT COUNTED") %>% 
  filter(incident_num != "NA") ### did this to make life easier
  1. (3 points) Are there any “hotspots” for shark incidents in California? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents per county. Which county has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
   ggplot(aes(county, fill = county)) + geom_bar() +coord_flip() + labs(title = "Hotspots for Incidents")

  1. (3 points) Are there months of the year when incidents are more likely to occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by month. Which month has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(month)) +geom_bar() + labs(title = "Number of Incidents by Month")

  1. (3 points) How do the number and types of injuries compare by county? Make a table (not a plot) that shows the number of injury types by county. Which county has the highest number of fatalities?
sharks %>%

  1. (2 points) In the data, mode refers to a type of activity. Which activity is associated with the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  group_by(mode) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(mode, fill = mode)) + geom_bar() + coord_flip() + labs(title = "Incidents by activity")

  1. (4 points) Use faceting to make a plot that compares the number and types of injuries by activity. (hint: the x axes should be the type of injury)
sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(injury, fill = injury)) + geom_bar() + facet_wrap(~mode) + labs(title = "Numbers and Types of Inuries by Activity")

  1. (1 point) Which shark species is involved in the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  group_by(species) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(species, fill = species)) + geom_bar() + labs(title = "Incidents by Species") + coord_flip()

  1. (3 points) Are all incidents involving Great White’s fatal? Make a plot that shows the number and types of injuries for Great White’s only.
sharks %>% 
  filter(species == "White") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(injury, fill = injury)) + geom_bar() + labs(title = "Count for Types of Injuries")

Background

Let’s learn a little bit more about Great White sharks by looking at a small dataset that tracked 20 Great White’s in the Fallaron Islands. The data are from: Weng et al. (2007) Migration and habitat of white sharks (Carcharodon carcharias) in the eastern Pacific Ocean.

Load the data

white_sharks <- read_csv("data/White sharks tracked from Southeast Farallon Island, CA, USA, 1999 2004.csv", na = c("?", "n/a")) %>% clean_names()

  1. (3 points) How do male and female sharks compare in terms of total length? Are males or females larger on average? Do a quick search online to verify your findings. (hint: this is a table, not a plot).
white_sharks %>% 
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  summarise(avg_length_by_sex = mean(total_length_cm))
## # A tibble: 3 × 2
##   sex   avg_length_by_sex
##   <chr>             <dbl>
## 1 F                  462 
## 2 M                  425.
## 3 <NA>               425

females are typically larger

  1. (3 points) Make a plot that compares the range of total length by sex.
white_sharks %>% 
  filter(sex != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sex, total_length_cm, color = sex)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(title = "Length by Sex")

  1. (2 points) Using the sharks or the white_sharks data, what is one question that you are interested in exploring? Write the question and answer it using a plot or table.
    ### Is total length affected by maturity? Is there a difference in how this affects males vs females?
white_sharks %>%
  filter(sex != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(maturity, total_length_cm, color = sex)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(title = "Length by Maturity and Sex")
